rComments: I grew in leaps and bounds during her course and as it ends, I feel like I have the necessary skills (combined with my practice in practicum) to be effective at an introductory level with families seeking therapy. She does not cover all readings in class, she focuses on getting students to practice skills you should be picking up in the readings.

I'm sure she's a good clinician, but Susan is one of the most disorganized professors I've ever had. She would talk about the details of concepts and activities in depth before explaining the most central pieces, which was incredibly confusing. She also never explained the assignments, and they were very vague and confusing.

SO CONFUSING! Literally talks in circles. Susan has vast practical wisdom and experience however, she is not a good teacher and blurs the course content. Did the course in a one-week intensive format, 8 hours a day, and left the last class feeling less confident in my clinical skills as my head was spinning. Nice lady though.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read', 'Participation matters']

rComments: The assignments are very vague in their guidelines and expectations. Susan is willing to meet with students, but I found myself coming out more confused than I was before. I have to agree with the above comment; Very disorganized. I enjoyed the class, but I felt that I could have done a lot better with some more concrete direction.

Very disorganized and does not seem to care about students.  One piece of advice: when you write the paper for this course, DO NOT sacrifice your orignial ideas unless you have already published them.
